                     <interp inst="def1-210-18421128" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-210-18421128" type="surname" value="GOLDSMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-210-18421128" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MARY GOLDSMITH</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18421128-210-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18421128-210-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="sexual"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18421128-210-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="bigamy"></interp>for bigamy.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1106" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1106" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1106" type="surname" value="ABEL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1106" type="given" value="SUSANNAH"></interp>SUSANNAH ABEL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Abel, and live in Hope-street, Spitalfields. The prisoner is my sister—she was married to Robert Gold<lb></lb>smith, at Hackney-church, on the 23rd of August, 1835—I was one of the subscribing witnesses—I was present at the same church, in Nov., 1837, when she was married to Daniel Sinfield—Goldsmiih has been dead three years and a half—when my sister was married last we considered him dead.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANX</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Goldsmith quarrel with her for not getting her property on the day. he was married? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the mar<lb></lb>riage was never consummated—Sinfield knaw that she had gone through the ceremony of marriage with Goldsmith—I told him that he was separated from my sister, and I considered he was dead—Sinfield had no property—my sister had a good house and furniture—he has ill-treated her. since, and she has had to go before the Magistrate nine times—he has held a threat of this charge to get her property from her, and he has got a portion of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1107" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1107" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1107" type="surname" value="SINFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1107" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID SINFIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I married the prisoner on the 16th of Nov., 1837—she never represented to me that she had been married before—she had on pro<lb></lb>perty whatever.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> After you were married, did you not go to live with her? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I did not take her to my house, because I had children—I had nothing of her—not a blanket or sheet to cover me at night—I have threatened to charge her with bigamy as soon as I could prove it.</p>
               <p>
